projection_comment: His PPR FPG finishes over the last five years are: WR1, WR1, WR1, WR2, and WR5 and that's all you need you need to know.
Has 10+ TGT/game but CR, YPR below league avg. in ugly year, but was still well above average with 1.8 PPR Pts per TGT and remains an elite talent.
He had at least 60 yards receiving and/or a TD in every single game 2017 and Watson will be back with more seasoning.
Became first WR in '17 to go over 1400 yards and score 3 or fewer TDs and his 28% TGT share likely to drop, but overall offense should improve in year 2 with OC Sarkeesian.
Amazingly averaged 15.5 FPG (WR11) w/ Rodgers and 16.3 FPG (WR6) w/o Rodgers and saw 35% of GB RZ targets, tying new teammed Graham for the highest rate in NFL.
His 196 catches most ever first 2 seasons by a WR and he's reached 60 yards and/or scored a TD in 79% of his career games, including playoffs.
Dalton’s 207.4 YPG last year was a career-low and well below career avg (234.3), so Green should elevate catch rate to 60% or better.
Over his last 25 games (2015-17 seasons), Allen's averaged 7/87.2 per game on 10.2 targets, only AB and Beckham better.
Bad year, but led TB in target share inside the 10 at 31%, but scored just one TD on his 9 targets, which is not sustainable so bound to bounce back.
Omitting his rookie year, Hilton has averaged 16.0 PPR FPG in career with Luck versus 11.3 FPG without him, and Luck's return promising in camp.
A nice 67.37% CR and a fantastic 2.09 FP per target and with QB upgrade and more pass-happy approach, he's a monster if healthy.
Very solid 14 YPR and only 16% share of TDs, so his catches/yardage were great, and a solid 1.68 FP/TGT and they will throw more.
Is WR12 in FPG (15.5) last 3 years and a whopping 216 TGT avail and 39% TGT inside the 10, and knee seems to be improving as of 8/17.
4th in targets with 10/game and his third straight year with 100+ catches and they have 2 QBs who can get him the rock.
Excellent 15.8 YPR, 73.4% catch rate as rookie and was WR5 with 18.2 FPG in the final 11 weeks and balling already in the preseason.
Will be hard to match 20.6% target share with Watkins added but outstanding 71.4 CR/15.7 YPR and excellent 2.3 FP per TGT and big plays coming with Mahomes.
Going for 90+ catches for 5th straight season as he enters his 30s and volume shouldn't be a problem with Ebron gone.
The #9 WR in total scoring through Week 8 and with Cooks/Amendola gone they have 240 vacated targets, plus Edelman out 4 games.
Confidence issues caused drop from 10th in Yds/Game in '16 to 47th in '17, but Gruden says he'll be major go-to guy and Oak has 13th-most vacated TGTs.
Continued to elevate his game in '17 and led NFL in YPR (18.1) among WRs with 50+ targets, but also great in contested catches and team-high 15 red-zone targets.
Won't likely get his 10 TGT/game as Browns have just 110 TGT and 19% avail, 11th-fewest, but Coleman trade helps his chances and they really need him.
Finished 27th out of 93 in yards gained per route run in '17 and QB play will be better, so a sneaky value pick.
Kind of a lost rookie season due to injury (ankle), but we loved his college tape and he flashed potential at times, like vs. NE in the playoffs (5/63/2 receiving)
Still only 24 when camp opens, he's 2 years removed from 80/1400/14 season and clear #1 on the outside.
Always has downside and a very poor 42% catch rate but 8+ TGT/game in 2017 and QBs will be much better, but camp no-show at least a mild concern overall.
Some availability issues lately, but has missed only 5 games last 6 years and upgraded QB makes him sneaky-appealing.
Was TD-dependent with 9 TDs and only a 47.5% CR and below Avg 1.58 PTs/TGT and also still banged up so shakier pick at ADP.
With Cooks/Amendola gone he should own the slot and Pats have a whopping 240 vacated targets, or 41%, which is 3rd most BUT staring at 4-game suspension.
Really nice job in '17 and good 9.16 yds/TGT/17.1 YPR and upside if he can stay healthy and improve terrible 1.9 TD % and clearly the #1.
Game is not based on speed so should be effective and Ravens have a whopping 332 vacated targets or 59%, which is the most in the league.
Had some drops but quickly assumed large role as a rookie and performed well with 65.96% CR, 9.25 YDs/TGT, and 1.88 Yds/TGT.
Posted a poor 60% CR and horrific 9.09 YPR, but does have a solid QB and role if he can still play, which it appears in camp he can.
Saw 25 fewer targets but finished as WR30 (11.8 FPG) just behind Alshon and a great 1.97 FP/TGT, and blowing up in camp in 2018.
Quickly emerged as vital cog with 9.19 yds/TGT and 13.95 YPR and a very good 1.92 FPs per TGT and they love him.
Rams have only 106 available targets (21%), 8th-fewest, so we can assume he'll get Watkins' targets and not much more, but he always has upside to go off.
Underwhelming '17 but his 19.07% TGT share should rise and QB Smith should quickly lean on him as his go-to guy unless TE Reed is somehow available.
Good player, but KC has only 76	vacated targets (14%), 6th fewest, and now a drop-off in production with Mahomes, but Watkins will have upside each week with QB's big arm.
Insane 14% TD and 80% RZ TD % and 2.26 FP per target impossible to duplicate, but shows off his upside any given week.
Might still be facing discipline from NFL, but balled out with strong 14.9 YPR, very good 6.14 TD %, healthy 22.3% TGT share, and 1.75 Yds/TGT.
Had some drops but a solid 70.2% CR, above-avg in Yds/TGT and strong 1.72 Pts/TGT and in a great spot with OBJ.
Actually had best catch rate ever at 62% and a solid 14.8 YPA and looked great in opener, but he's limited and should have a weak QB no matter what.
Improved catch rate to a still-poor 56.8%, but YPR fell to career-low 13.3,
Only 58% CR and 12.5 YPR, but only 12% of his scoring came from TD so with some luck he could surprise, yet a little crowded at WR here.
49ers have 8th-fewest available targets at 18% but he should be top passing target with a good QB now in Jimmy G.
Mia has 290 targets avail (49% share), 2nd-most, and a nice 14.6 YPR and a strong 1.66 FP per TGT, so a nice depth guy with upside.
Could be sneaky option as he's averaged 3.9/58 per game over the last 2 years and WRs group thinned and he's not hurt!
Impressive 72% CR with Rodgers missing so much time and sneaky upside after he averaged strong 1.71 FP/TGT, but he's been banged up and is now looking at trade rumors.
Sneaky pick in FA year with 41% of their 2017 targets and 39% of their looks inside the 10 off roster, but Marshall if he has anything left will take some looks.
Dynamic athlete who can play inside or outside and has the potential to be the top playmaker at WR immediately and good showing in opener.
He's a very good deep threat and no QB had better QB Rating on deep passes than Alex Smith, so worth a shot for depth later in drafts.
His rookie 2016 season was a red shirt year and he has a lot of talent, but more injury issues in 2018 so we're almost giving up on him.
Finished '17 career lows in YPG (47.7), YPR (13.4), longest reception (41), and FPG finish (WR49) and now Godwin is coming on strong so D-jax must be cheap.
Taken 81st overall and a chance to play immediately as he's shown well in camp and in preseason opener, but lacks any clear outstanding qualities.
If healthy he's the #2 and deep threat, and 59% of their 2017 targets are off roster, and Brown is healthy and showing well this summer.
His 2017 4.3 TGT/game should rise so upside as he posted excellent 9.94 yds per TGT, 1.94 FP/TGT, and 17.4 YPR
Bit of a tweener prospect, probably best playing out of the slot but capable of playing outside too, and showing very well this summer.
Pitiful 47.8% CR and 8.6 YPR in injury-marred rookie year and only 70 vacated targets (5th-fewest) but he does have plenty of ability and potential.
Best separator in '18 class, slides in perfectly as the Z receiver, playing across from Julio and alongside Sanu so has a chance to be impactful.
Showed a ton of promise out of nowhere in 2016 with 66/888/4 and in a good spot...if his knee is OK this summer.
Not a special athlete by any stretch, but his 69% CR was solid and did have an impressive 1.94 FP per TGT last year and they need him.
A strong 70% catch rate but his 6.4 TGT/game likely dropping with Ridley added, so a depth guy only.
He's started 24 out of 43 possible games and continues to drive us nuts, and it's getting worse not better in 2018.
Amazing 75.7% CR/14.8 YPR but only 61 available targets from '17 and if Meredith is healthy that's a problem.
Solid 62% CR with his 15.4 YPR and a good 1.68 FP/TGT and quickly proving he's too good to keep off the field, likely pushing DJax to slot.
Has a chance in PPR as Mia has 290 targets avail (49% share), 2nd-most, and clicking early with Tannehill, but  Wilson will challenge for snaps and targets.
Not overly talented but good size for the outside and did have 70% CR in '17 and is at 14 YPR for career, yet quiet so far in Aug.
Only a 53% CR but did step into large role quickly with 7.3 TGT/game and was balling in the preseason, so solid sleeper.
Another strong showing with 62.3% CR and 16.9 YPR but too many WRs here and even poor 11.8% TGT share will be tough to match.
Came out of nowhere and posted 17.8 YPR and strong 1.6 FP per TGT, but will be tough to match his 15.75% target share, yet he's in line to start.
Brutal rookie season with 2 targets and 0 catches but he's a first-round talent and too early to give up on totally, and great opportunity in 2018.
He's clearly been making plays this summer and looks like a sneaky option here with the potential to be surprise WW guy.
Poor 52% CR and 12 YPR and even a poor RZ TD% at 22% so that's why he's looking for a new team.
Will step right into Bryant’s old spot as deep threat who gets single coverage with AB and JuJu soaking up attention.
Numbers aren't flashy, but he's shown a lot with minimal snaps and now 151 targets are vacated, or 27%, which is 13th most, and he's the 3.
Showed a lot of juice as a gadget player in rookie '17 season and nice role as their slot/WR3 job.
Underrated and has a chance with 290 targets avail (49% share), 2nd-most, but might be a better WW guy with Amendola well in the mix in the slot.
Eagles have a decent 28% open target share and he's big upgrade over Torrey Smith and he can still run at 14.4 YPR so decent bench/depth guy.
His 2-season average of a 42% catch rate and 12.8 YPR isn't cutting it and bad QB play likely in Buff, but he will play a lot due to his speed.
Could face suspension after alcohol-related arrest in May, which could cost him his job, but key starter still for now.
Bad year in 2017 with below-average 7.18 YDs/TGT and 1.55 FP/TGT and likely suspended first 4 games, but he can still make big plays.
Impressive in '16 but fell off a cliff in '17 with horrible 57% CR/8.7 YPR but Dal is very lacking at receiver with 56% of '17 targets gone.
Very good prospect, but he profiles best as a playmaker out of the slot so his role will bear watching with Larry there.
If he can win the slot job with a fresh start in Bal, he'll have PPR value as there are 332 vacated targets or 59%, which is the most in the league.
Has the talent to be a starter here and showing very well in Aug, including huge effort in opener, but major off-field issue including a weed-related problem that popped up 8/7.
Smooth, graceful possession receiver in the mold of Alshon, and should play quickly on outside as Sanders/DT can slide into slot, and showing well in camp.
Seemed to climb out of dog house late in season and caught game-winning 49-yard TD Week 17, and LaFell gone helps a lot.
Surprised with 64% CR and 5 TDs but unlikely to get his 2017 20% TGT share with several young prospects on the roster.
He should be in the mix for a starting job, but they have a deep WR group and they like Chad Hansen a lot.
Drafted to eventually be Ginn’s replacement as Brees’ downfield threat, and opening eyes in camp this summer.
Vikes have only 110 vacated targets, 10th-fewest and he's not running as well, but savvy player who should help them in the slot.
Vikes have only 110 vacated targets, 10th-fewest but he's actually coming on and looks like the #3.
Horrific 36.4% catch rate as a rookie, but he did show signs of life later, and he's at least practicing now as of mid-Aug.
Explosive athlete who could be a vertical threat out of the slot and push Braxton Miller to the side, but needs work on route-running to become a complete interior receiver.
A return dynamo, he could easily use his speed and shiftiness to carve out a role in the slot, but has to excel in camp to have a chance as a rookie.
Solid in his role as deep threat with 16.7 YPR but only 70 vacated targets and a lot of those will go to Mike Williams.
Did average 15 YPR last year but has missed multiple games last 2 years and signed only 1-year deal with run-heavy and WR-crowded Jags.
Only 54% CR and 1 TD in ugly 2017 season and plenty of competition for snaps and targets, so we'll see if he can stand out in camp.
Underrated slot receiver who knows Norv's offense well from Min and should have leg up over Samuel, but we need to see his role in camp.
At worst a rotational deep threat and WR3 and with improved coaching he's capable of the 16.5 YPR/70% CR he posted in 2016.
They need him and NE likely to use him in creative ways to get him in space.
Serviceable slot guy who could catch 50-60 balls if he wins job, but the rookie Pettis has a lot more upside.
Only 12.6 YPR last 2 years with a terrible 46.8% catch rate, but they'll try him for shot plays and Cam does have a gun.
A dreadful 18/154/0 with 8.6 YPR on the Giants last year so he may have fallen off a cliff but Sea likes his size and he should get on the field.
Slipped a bit to the 6th round, but big (6’2”, 202 pounds) and fast outside WR, but hurt in preseason opener.
Still young and talented and will get snaps but fellow 2017 draftee Gibson is really coming on and has more speed.
He's looked like dog dirt with a career 51% catch rate and 9.2 YPR, which is awful.
One of the the most pedestrian starters in the league but targets will be hard to come by if Ross and Eifert are factors.
Not really standing out in camp, but they have to play him with Cain on IR and little behind TH and Grant.
A 3rd round pick last year, he's a good prospect with size and they like him, so should get a chance to carve large role.
He'll be down on depth chart, but an excellent route runner and showed more athleticism in tests than otherwise thought.
We'll have to see when final cuts come down but he's likely making this team and nice upside.
Only 25 catches in 2 seasons and not a great sign they brought in FAs Brown/Snead plus Crabtree.
Working in camp after serious ankle injury and played well in opener, but looks like gadget player only.
Interesting guy who was at 21 YPR in 2017, but has never caught more than 21 balls in a season, so just a deep sleeper to watch.
He's been playing WR in camp despite talk of him swtching to RB, but not draftable.
Poor stats due to LSU’s terrible passing attack and crowded WR group here, but eye-popping vertical profile with 4.34 40-time at 6’3”, 199 pounds.
Talented guy who will compete with Nelson, Butler, and Kirk for #2 WR job, but little will be known until August.
Has never caught more than 34 passes in a season, but Cardinals have 243 targets available (41% share), 4th-most, so there's an opportunity.
Making plays again this summer and there will definitely be a role for him as a rotational player and shot play guy.
Almost time to give up on this former college QB's attempt to play WR and with Keke Coutee added in the draft he'll be lucky to get one more chance.
Britt became the third WR (after Matthews and Mitchell) to be cut by the Pats this off-season so forget it.
Lost rookie 2017 to injury and they added 2 good WRs in draft, but dynamic with ball in his hands and will get a chance to push for playing time.
He gives them size but has struggled in camp, so may be destined for practice squad.
He's been released by the Patriots, which is a terrible sign.
He's 31 now but will get another opportunity on a team thin at WR like the NYG.
Caught a solid 32 out of 48 targets in 2016 so he can produce here with 240 available targets, but we'll see about Kenny Britt's potential role.
Just turned 30 in May but his YPR has dropped three years in a row and his worst CR of 55.6% in 2017, and probably a WR3 for team that signs him at best.
